-      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Year-long field study of 5,179 customer support agents at a Fortune 500 software firm | Source: VERIFIED (Brynjolfsson, Li, Raymond, \"Generative AI at Work,\" NBER Working Paper 31161, April 2023, revised — methodology section)\nClaim: Half worked with a generative AI assistant trained on the company's own chat history | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — study design; AI tool was an LLM-based conversational assistant trained on prior chat transcripts)\nClaim: 14% more issues resolved per hour across the full sample | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — headline finding: 14% increase in issues resolved per hour)\nClaim: 34% productivity lift for novice agents in their first months | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — the largest effects concentrated among newer/lower-skilled workers, with bottom-quintile gains around 34%)\nClaim: Senior agents at the top of the curve gained almost nothing | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — effects diminish toward zero for experienced/high-performing agents)\nClaim: AI assistant encoded the moves of top-performing agents from the firm's own corpus | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — mechanism analysis: training corpus drew on successful chat patterns; effect operates by diffusing tacit knowledge of high performers to low performers)\nClaim: Week 6 Challenge is to trace one external output — what Claude produced, what you changed, why | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html, Week 6 Challenge text: \"Find one output you sent externally this week. Trace it like the example above: what did Claude produce, what did you change, and why? Bring the trace to Friday.\")\nClaim: Week 6 opens capstone Project Scope (Section 1) and Workflow Draft (Section 2) | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html, Opens Week 6 badge: \"Begin your capstone: Project Scope (Section 1) and Workflow Draft (Section 2). Bring your draft to Week 7 for peer review.\")\nEditorial: Framing the Brynjolfsson trace-of-top-performers as the same move as the pilot's Week 6 trace exercise is Preston's pedagogical synthesis, not language used by the authors.\nEditorial: \"Once a move is traced, it can be reused. Once it is reused, it stops belonging to you\" is Preston's framing of the tacit-to-explicit knowledge transfer mechanism the paper describes empirically.\nEditorial: Resource URL is the NBER abstract page for WP 31161; if the link resolves stale, the canonical citation (NBER WP 31161, April 2023) remains accurate and discoverable by title search. The paper was published as Brynjolfsson, Li, Raymond, \"Generative AI at Work,\" Quarterly Journal of Economics, 2025.\nAdversarial review 20260511 (rev 1): Em-dash count: 0 (under the 2-per-piece limit). Forbidden phrases scanned and absent: leverage, utilize, delve, navigate (metaphorical), landscape, ecosystem, synergy, robust, holistic, stakeholders, foster, enhance, align, transformative, empower, myriad, multifaceted, pivotal, nuanced (filler), spearhead, showcase, underscore, doing the heavy lifting, the real question is, what most people miss, this is where it gets interesting, move the needle, at the end of the day, deep dive, unpack. Contrastive constructions (\"X, not Y\" / \"not X, but Y\") scanned and absent. Rhetorical questions in body: zero. Opens with concrete fact (year-long study, 5,179 agents, Fortune 500 software firm). \"However/Moreover/Furthermore/Additionally\": zero. Word count main body: 273 (inside 240–280 band). Try This: 63 (inside 40–80 band). Try This precisely mirrors the Week 6 Challenge (one external output, trace what changed and why) and routes the trace into the capstone Project starter file, so the briefing and the live curriculum reinforce the same action.",
+      "resource": "https://www.anthropic.com/news/the-anthropic-economic-index",
+      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Anthropic published its first Economic Index in February 2025 | Source: VERIFIED (Anthropic, \"The Anthropic Economic Index,\" published February 10, 2025; companion paper Handa et al., \"Which Economic Tasks are Performed with AI? Evidence from Millions of Claude Conversations\")\nClaim: Roughly four million anonymized Claude.ai conversations analyzed | Source: VERIFIED (same release — approximately 4 million Claude.ai Free and Pro conversations included in the sample after privacy filtering)\nClaim: Conversations mapped to the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics task framework (O*NET) | Source: VERIFIED (same release — methodology uses the O*NET database, sponsored by the U.S. Department of Labor / BLS, to classify tasks)\nClaim: Software and tech work led at about 37% of all conversations | Source: VERIFIED (same release — Computer and Mathematical occupations accounted for ~37.2% of Claude conversations)\nClaim: Writing and creative work came next at roughly 10% | Source: VERIFIED (same release — Arts, Design, Entertainment, Sports, and Media occupations accounted for ~10.3% of conversations, the second-largest category)\nClaim: Education and training rounded out the top three at about 9% | Source: VERIFIED (same release — Educational Instruction and Library occupations accounted for ~9.3%, the third-largest category)\nClaim: Roughly 36% of US occupations now have measurable Claude use (AI used in at least a quarter of their associated tasks) | Source: VERIFIED (same release — \"AI is used for at least 25% of associated tasks within approximately 36% of occupations\")\nClaim: Week 6 challenge is to find one externally sent piece and trace what Claude produced, what you changed, and why | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html, Week 6 Challenge text: \"Find one output you sent externally this week. Trace it like the example above: what did Claude produce, what did you change, and why? Bring the trace to Friday.\")\nEditorial: \"Treat the trace as the answer to a question Anthropic could not see from outside\" is Preston's framing connecting population-level conversation data to individual-level practice.\nEditorial: The pivot from \"where AI shows up at work\" (Anthropic's question) to \"whether your particular use of it got better this week\" (the pilot's question) is Preston's pedagogical bridge, not language from the source.\nEditorial: Resource URL is the Anthropic news page for the Economic Index launch; the underlying methodology paper is co-released and discoverable from that page. Both resources remain authoritative for the cited figures.\nAdversarial review 20260511 (rev 2): Em-dash count: 0 (under the 2-per-piece limit). Forbidden phrases scanned and absent: leverage, utilize, delve, navigate (metaphorical), landscape, ecosystem, synergy, robust, holistic, stakeholders, foster, enhance, align, transformative, empower, myriad, multifaceted, pivotal, nuanced (filler), spearhead, showcase, underscore, doing the heavy lifting, the real question is, what most people miss, this is where it gets interesting, deep dive, unpack, move the needle, at the end of the day, groundbreaking, tapestry. Contrastive constructions scanned and absent. Rhetorical questions in body: zero. Opens with a concrete relatable fact (you probably used Claude for writing last week). However/Moreover/Furthermore/Additionally: zero. Word count main body: 260 (inside 240-280 band). Try This: 57 (inside 40-80 band). Source is February 2025 (15 months old, recent) and is the original Economic Index release, distinct from the September 2025 update referenced in the May 8 news entry. Tone is deliberately more introductory than rev 1: second-person opening, no research methodology jargon in the first sentence, every percentage anchored to a familiar job category, Try This action is one piece of writing rather than a research extraction.",
